metadata.name: Mooncakes: Happy Mid Autumn Festival 2022 #491
metadata.description:
To celebrate the Moon Festival with Mooncakes, we have created a quest to introduce everyone to fxhash. As part of that quest on mooncakes.fun, users are encouraged to mint this generative token.

This is a layered image composition using the Mooncakes site images on a 1920x1080 canvas. The image elements are randomly assigned position, scale, tint, and blur according to a ruleset which generates a Mid Autumn Festival scene made up of: Moon, Clouds, Stars, Lanterns, and Lotuses.

Special filters, shapes and colors are included as rare features, as well as a couple of surprises.

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #340
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

License: CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ - @jakub_antolak

———
*choose your option

metadata.name: In the Edge #1
metadata.description:
./ In the Edge

It's been a long time since your journey began, caring for the ones you love, pursuing your dreams, and giving the best of you. 

Now you know you can't go back, you can't go further, you know your time is coming.

How far did you go? It doesn't matter, you did it right. Your accomplishments will serve well the next generations in their journeys, in their search for themselves.

Now it's time to stop, time to take a moment and contemplate the vast universe.

Soon all of this will be ending.

You did it right.

Embrace the void.
=========
=========


./ Color scheme (feature)
There are 12 color schemes and with each set, specific arrays for color collections for the space, stars, planet, and accent colors. 

These are color schemes in the known universe of "In the Edge":
- Mars visions
- Cyberpunk
- Unknown passenger 
- Renegade
- Primary
- Coral
- r.e.d.
- Machines of an ancient-future 
- The void
- Tinted light 
- Malibu dreams
- Atari (horrendous brown, red and yellowish combinations... I love it)

./ Mountain type (feature)
In the Edge, you will find a mountain, and that mountain will be special, which type will you find?

- Parallela insolitum
- Sandy dunes of the truth
- Wavy uncertainty
- Intrinsic soul ridges
- Cerritulus formationis

./ Mountain direction (feature)
Life is about direction... mountains too.

- Left
- Right
- Left-Right

./ Space scenery
This is the spicy touch, some of the iterations will have animation and others will not, giving you a clear view of the magnificent space in front of you.

- Clean (NOT animated)
- Windy planet (animated)
- Topographic planet (animated)
- Meteor shower (animated)

./ Distance from Earth (feature)
How far did you go? Your travel could be from 1 lightyear to 999,999,999 lightyears (that's a lot of lights and years!). However just a few will pass the barrier of 99,999,999ly.

// Additional perks
./ Planet names 
Planet names are unique and they are conformed by three blocks.

The first block is a conjunction between ancient Latin names and Japanese last names. 

The second block takes the last three characters from the fxhash.

The third block takes three numbers from the number seed obtained from fxrand().

The planet you land will be unique, as unique as you are.

// Controls
./ Pause-Play animation
Because maybe (and just maybe) you want to freeze the perfect moment before closing your eyes.

[Backspace] Pause.
[Enter] Play

Applies to "Space scenery" features windy planet, topographic planet, and meteor shower.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #44
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Sedimentary Dissolution #44
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the geological processes related to sedimentary dissolution. Dissolution is a form of weathering which contributes to the creation of new rocks. In this piece, various algorithms take on the role of dissolution, producing visual recombinations of the original "sedimentary rock".

Instructions ::

p : save a hi-res image
e : toggle erosion on and off
s : toggle structure on and off
a : toggle all effects on and off

If offset, rgb dissolution or cross-bedding is true you can toggle it on and off.
If these features are false pressing the key will have no effect.

o : toggle offset on and off
r : toggle rgb dissolution on and off
c : toggle cross-bedding on and off

There are 20 versions you can explore, all using the same features.
Use the left and right arrow to change the random seed. 
Pressing space will re-instantiate the original random seed.

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #14
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #2 Moonrise by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: The Abstract Truth III #156
metadata.description:
Moiré patterns meet halftone dots meet cross stitching.

Halftone is a term that can refer to both a technology used in image processing and as the synonym for semitone in music. A jazz musician Oliver Nelson released the album The Blues and the Abstract Truth in 1961. It is considered one of the most significant records of its time. In addition, he wrote Patterns for Improvisation, a hugely popular jazz patterns book. The Moiré pattern design is on the book's cover.

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations. 
Press 'P' to pause/unpause the animation.

metadata.name: PolyGarden #199
metadata.description:
Polygons, patterns and flowers are mixtured in my garden. I start with a birdeye view of the garden and its geometric structure. The species diversity and the random stack of rocks, sands, fences and other objects are main structures I want to capture, in an abstract and planar style. 

Moreover, in this project, I also try to explore the representation ability of generative art. I select three elements: shape of entity, layout of palette, and stack of object location. The factors behind these elements are the balance of randomness and structure: the generative art generates the variants from randomness but restricts its chaos with structure (deterministic constraints) to represent the meaningful results. 

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 6 texture patterns
- 15 color palette
- 3 randomness
- 2 completeness

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: fabrics #10
metadata.description:
'fabrics' explores textile art made with code mixing different patterns of very small lines.

Inspiration from Anni Albers works, Antoni Tàpies and Studio Yorktown for the patterns and the colours. Also oriental rugs and clothes from around the world had been used for the palettes.
Palettes: Monochrome, Kilt, Kilim, Austral, Peruvian, Afghan, Berber, Nain, Fur, Jeans, Kente, Bogolan, Albers, Sabler.

Press [s] to save an 1200x1360 image (.png).
Click on it to change the orientation of the stitches.

Generative art made using p5js. By @mehno_art

metadata.name: Lepidoptera #46
metadata.description:
I love trying to capture the textures and colors found in nature and reproduce them with code. Lepidoptera is inspired by the species of the same name.

Features include: color palette, medium hatching count, large hatching count, noise offset, and noise level.

p5.js
